    <h2>1.1.1 Atoms, elements and compounds</h2>
    <p>
        - All substances are made up of atoms, which are the smallest part 
        of an element that can exist.<br>
        - Atoms are represented by a symbol, for example <code>H</code> for hydrogen.<br>
        - There are 118 known elements, and each element has a unique symbol and position 
        on the periodic table.<br>
        - Compounds are formed from elements by chemical reactions.<br>
        - Reactions always involve the formation of one or more new substances and 
        often involve a detectable energy change.<br>
        - Compounds contain two or more elements chemically combined in
        fixed proportions and can be represented by formulae using the
        symbols of the atoms from which they were formed.<br>
        - Compounds can only be separated into elements by chemical reactions.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h2>Equations</h2>
    <p>
        - Here is an example of a chemical reaction:<br>
        <code>2H<sub>2</sub> + O<sub>2</sub>{" -> 2H"}<sub>2</sub>O</code><br>
        - In that reaction, 4 hydrogen atoms (2x2; as hydrogen does not exist naturally 
        as a single atom), and 2 oxygen atoms (oxygen also doesn't exist as a single atom) 
        are combined to form 2 water molecules.<br>
        - That equation is <i>balanced</i>, meaning that the number of atoms of each 
        element is the same on both sides of the equation.<br>
        - The unbalanced equation would be:<br>
        <code>H<sub>2</sub> + O<sub>2</sub>{" -> H"}<sub>2</sub>O</code><br>
        - Here, there is one oxygen atom left over, which you can't have.<br><br>
        - Equations can also be ionic (show electrical charge), for example:<br>
        <code>H<sup>+</sup> + OH<sup>-</sup>{" ->"} H<sub>2</sub>O</code><br>
        - Here, the hydrogen ion gains an electron, and the hydroxide ion loses one, in a neutralisation 
        reaction to form water (more on this later).<br><br>
        - Chemical reactions can be represented by word equations or equations using 
        symbols and formulae. For example, the reaction to form water above would be 
        written as <code>{"Hydrogen + Oxygen -> Water"}</code>.
    </p>
    <br>
    <h2>1.1.2 Mixtures</h2>
    <p>
        - A mixture consists of two or more elements or compounds <b>not</b> chemically combined together.<br>
        - The chemical properties of each substance in the mixture are unchanged.<br>
        - Mixtures can be separated by physical processes such as filtration,
        crystallisation, simple distillation, fractional distillation and
        chromatography. These physical processes do not involve chemical
        reactions and no new substances are made.
    </p>
    <Table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Separation Method</th>
                <th>Description</th>
                <th>Explanation</th>
                <th>When to Use</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>Filtration</td>
                <td>Separates an insoluble solid from a liquid.</td>
                <td>
                    Filtration involves pouring a mixture through filter paper placed in a funnel. The paper has tiny
                    pores that allow only liquids and very fine particles to pass through. The solid particles, which
                    are too large to pass through the pores, are trapped on the paper (called the residue). The liquid
                    that passes through is collected in a container below and is called the filtrate. This process does
                    not change the substances; it only separates them based on particle size.
                </td>
                <td>
                    Use when separating a solid that does not dissolve in a liquid, like sand from water or coffee
                    grounds from brewed coffee.
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Crystallisation</td>
                <td>Obtains a dissolved solid (solute) from a solution.</td>
                <td>
                    Crystallisation works by forming solid crystals from a solution. The solution is first gently heated
                    to partially evaporate the solvent (usually water), increasing the concentration of the solute. Once
                    it becomes saturated—meaning no more solute can dissolve—the mixture is left to cool slowly. As the
                    temperature drops, the solute particles come out of solution and form an orderly crystal structure.
                    Impurities remain in the solution and are left behind when the crystals are filtered and dried.
                </td>
                <td>
                    Use when recovering pure crystals from a solution, like forming salt crystals from seawater or
                    copper sulfate crystals from a laboratory solution.
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Simple Distillation</td>
                <td>Separates a solvent from a solution.</td>
                <td>
                    Simple distillation uses the difference in boiling points between a solvent and solute. The solution
                    is heated until the solvent (which has a lower boiling point) boils and turns into vapor. This vapor
                    is then directed into a condenser, where it cools and turns back into liquid. The remaining solute,
                    which doesn’t evaporate, stays in the original container. This method is best when separating a
                    single solvent from a non-volatile solute, like salt in saltwater.
                </td>
                <td>
                    Use when extracting pure solvent from a solution, such as getting distilled water from tap water.
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Fractional Distillation</td>
                <td>Separates a mixture of liquids based on their boiling points.</td>
                <td>
                    Fractional distillation is an extension of simple distillation and is used for mixtures of liquids
                    with similar boiling points. The mixture is heated and vapors rise up a fractionating column, which
                    is packed with glass beads or plates to provide a surface for repeated condensation and
                    vaporisation. Substances with lower boiling points rise higher in the column and are collected
                    first, while those with higher boiling points condense lower down. This allows each component to be
                    separated more precisely.
                </td>
                <td>
                    Use when separating mixtures like ethanol and water, or in industry for refining crude oil into
                    petrol, diesel, and other products.
                </td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>Chromatography</td>
                <td>Separates components of a mixture based on how they travel through a medium.</td>
                <td>
                    Chromatography relies on differences in solubility and how substances interact with a stationary
                    phase (like paper) and a mobile phase (like a solvent). A small spot of the mixture is placed near
                    the bottom of chromatography paper. When the paper is placed in a solvent, the solvent travels up
                    the paper, carrying the components of the mixture with it. Substances that are more soluble in the
                    solvent move further up the paper, while those that are less soluble move more slowly. This
                    separates the components visibly.
                </td>
                <td>
                    Use when separating or identifying substances in dyes, inks, or food colorings, especially when only
                    small amounts are available.
                </td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </Table>
