    <h2>1.1.3 The development of the model of the atom</h2>
    <p>
        - In science, new experimental evidence may lead to a scientific model being
        changed or replaced.<br>
    </p>
    <h3>Solid Sphere & Plum Pudding</h3>
    <p>
        - Before the discovery of the electron, atoms were thought to be tiny
        spheres that could not be divided. Simply the <b>solid sphere</b> model, proposed by John Dalton in 1803.<br>
        - The discovery of the electron led to the <b>plum pudding</b> model of the
        atom. The plum pudding model suggested that the atom is a ball of
        positive charge with negative electrons embedded in it. This was proposed by J.J. Thomson in 1897.
        <img class="centreimage" src="/images/ch/plumpudding.png" alt="plum pudding">
        <sub>CC BY-SA, from <a href="https://www.wikilectures.eu/w/File:Plumpuding.png">WikiLectures</a></sub><br>
    </p>
    <h3>The alpha particle scattering experiment & nuclear model</h3>
    <p>
        - The experiment, carried out by Ernest Rutherford and his colleagues Hans Geiger and Ernest Marsden in 1909, involved 
        firing alpha particles (positively charged particles) at a thin gold foil. Behind the foil, a detector screen coated 
        with zinc sulfide would light up whenever an alpha particle hit it, allowing the scientists to track the scattering patterns of the particles.<br>
        - Most alpha particles passed straight through the gold foil with very little deflection, indicating that atoms are mostly empty space.<br>
        - Some alpha particles were deflected at small angles, and a few were scattered back at very large angles, even bouncing straight back toward the source.
        <img class="centreimage" src="/images/ch/alphaparticlescattering.webp" alt="alpha particle scattering">
        <sub>CC BY, from <a href="https://pressbooks.online.ucf.edu/phy2053tjb/chapter/discovery-of-the-parts-of-the-atom-electrons-and-nuclei/">UCF Pressbooks</a></sub><br>
        - These observations led Rutherford to propose that atoms have a tiny, dense, positively charged nucleus at their centre as most of the atom was 
        shown to be empty space.<br>
        - The nucleus contains most of the atom's mass and repels the positively charged alpha particles when they come close to it.<br>
        - This nuclear model replaced the plum pudding model.
        <img class="centreimage" src="/images/ch/nuclear.webp" alt="nuclear model">
    </p>
    <h3>The Planetary (Bohr) model</h3>
    <p>
        Niels Bohr adapted the nuclear model by suggesting that electrons
        orbit the nucleus at specific distances. The theoretical calculations
        of Bohr agreed with experimental observations.
        <img class="centreimage" src="/images/ch/planetary.png" alt="bohr model">
    </p>
    <h3>Developments in the nucleus</h3>
    <p>
        - Later experiments led to the idea that the positive charge of any
        nucleus could be subdivided into a whole number of smaller
        particles, each particle having the same amount of positive charge.
        - The name proton was given to these particles.<br>
        The experimental work of James Chadwick provided the evidence
        to show the existence of neutrons within the nucleus. This was
        about 20 years after the nucleus became an accepted scientific
        idea.
    </p>
